The '''CHIPS and Science Act''' is a U.S. federal statute enacted by the [[117th United States Congress]] and signed into law by President [[Joe Biden]] on August 9, 2022. The act authorizes roughly $280 billion in new funding to boost domestic research and manufacturing of [[semiconductors]] in the United States, for which it appropriates $52.7 billion.<ref name="Politico 20220809">{{Cite web |last=Johnson |first=Lamar |date=August 9, 2022 |title=Biden ends slog on semiconductor bill with signature |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/08/09/biden-ends-slog-on-semiconductor-bill-with-signature-00050530 |access-date=August 9, 2022 |website=[[POLITICO]] |language=en |quote=Biden said Micron, an American-based company, announced a 10-year, $40 billion investment on Tuesday for factories and building memory chips as a result of the law. He also touted a Monday announcement by American companies Qualcomm and GlobalFoundries to invest $4 billion to produce semiconductors in the United States. |archive-date=August 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220821173945/https://www.politico.com/news/2022/08/09/biden-ends-slog-on-semiconductor-bill-with-signature-00050530 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Congressional Research Service |date=April 25, 2023 |title=Frequently Asked Questions: CHIPS Act of 2022 Provisions and Implementation |url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R47523 |website=United States Congressional Research Service}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Zimmerman |first=Alessandra |date=August 26, 2022 |title=R&D Funding Breakdown: CHIPS and Science Act |url=https://www.aaas.org/sites/default/files/2023-01/CHIPS%20AAE.pdf?adobe_mc=MCMID%3D69209921711590814772918205876201604040%7CMCORGID%3D242B6472541199F70A4C98A6%2540AdobeOrg%7CTS%3D1701808990 |website=American Association for the Advancement of Science}}</ref> 
The act includes $39&nbsp;billion in subsidies for chip manufacturing on U.S. soil along with 25% investment tax credits for costs of manufacturing equipment, and $13&nbsp;billion for semiconductor research and workforce training, with the dual aim of strengthening American [[supply chain resilience]] and countering [[China]].<ref name="Economist_2023-03-06">{{Cite news |date=2023-03-06 |title=Taiwan's dominance of the chip industry makes it more important – No industry matters more to Taiwan than chipmaking |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2023/03/06/taiwans-dominance-of-the-chip-industry-makes-it-more-important |url-status=live |quote=America is also trying to stop China getting advanced chips. It passed the CHIPS and Science Act in August 2022, offering $39bn in subsidies and a 25% tax credit to promote manufacturing at home, as well as $13bn of investment in chip research. In October 2022 it banned the export of advanced chips and chipmaking gear to China. |access-date=March 11, 2023 |archive-date=March 11, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311010040/https://www.economist.com/special-report/2023/03/06/taiwans-dominance-of-the-chip-industry-makes-it-more-important }}</ref>{{ r | SJMN_2022-09-04 | p=1 | q=The CHIPS and Science Act aims to create a new world order. The $280 billion package includes $39 billion to help with the financing of semiconductor fabrication, assembly, testing and advanced packaging, as well as $13.2 billion toward research and workforce development. It also provides a 25% investment tax credit for capital costs of manufacturing equipment. }} It also invests $174 billion in the overall ecosystem of public sector research in science and technology, advancing [[human spaceflight]], [[quantum computing]], [[materials science]], [[biotechnology]], [[experimental physics]], research security, social and ethical considerations, workforce development and [[diversity, equity, and inclusion]] efforts at [[NASA]], [[National Science Foundation|NSF]], [[United States Department of Energy|DOE]], [[Economic Development Administration|EDA]], and [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]].<ref name="McKinsey 2022" /><ref name="CSIS 2 2022" /><ref name="Atlantic 20220810"/><ref name="AIP 2022"/><ref name="Energy.gov 2023 anniversary press release"/><ref name="Guston 2023"/>

The act does not have an official short title as a whole but is divided into three divisions with their own short titles: Division A is the '''CHIPS Act of 2022''' (where CHIPS stands for the former ''"Creating Helpful Incentives to Produce Semiconductors" for America Act''<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 14, 2022 |title=CHIPS for America Seeks Public Input on Financial Incentives, New Institutes for Semiconductor Manufacturing |url=https://www.commerce.gov/ |access-date=2024-12-18 |website=U.S. Department of Commerce |archive-date=October 14, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221014131149/https://www.commerce.gov/news/blog/2022/10/chips-america-seeks-public-input-financial-incentives-new-institutes |url-status=live }}</ref>); Division B is the '''Research and Development, Competition, and Innovation Act'''; and Division C is the '''Supreme Court Security Funding Act of 2022'''.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 9, 2022 |title=Text – H.R.4346 – 117th Congress (2021–2022): Supreme Court Security Funding Act of 2022 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/4346/text |access-date=2022-09-11 |website=U.S. Congress |archive-date=May 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200517224927/http://www.congress.gov/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

By March 2024, analysts estimated that the act incentivized between 25 and 50 separate potential projects, with total projected investments of $160–200 billion and 25,000–45,000 new jobs. However, these projects are faced with delays in receiving grants due to bureaucratic hurdles, shortages of skilled workers, and congressional funding deals that have limited or cut research provisions of the Act by tens of billions of dollars.<ref name=WSJ_2024-01-27 /><ref name="Brookings 2023"/><ref name="Mui 2024"/>

== History ==
The '''CHIPS and Science Act''' combines two bipartisan bills: the '''Endless Frontier Act''',<ref>{{Cite web |title=Congressional Bill |date=May 21, 2020 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/3832 |access-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-date=November 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221127192918/https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/3832 |url-status=live }}</ref> designed to boost investment in domestic high-tech research, and the '''CHIPS for America Act''',<ref>{{Cite web |title=Congressional Bill |date=June 11, 2020 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/7178 |access-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/7178 |url-status=live }}</ref> designed to bring semiconductor manufacturing back to the U.S. The act is aimed at competing with China.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2014 |title=Bipartisan support for US science more likely in Senate than House |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1063/pt.5.028154 |journal=Physics Today |issue=8 |page=6419 |doi=10.1063/pt.5.028154 |bibcode=2014PhT..2014h6419. |issn=1945-0699 |access-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-date=May 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230503215855/https://pubs.aip.org/physicstoday/Online/6419/Bipartisan-support-for-US-science-more-likely-in |url-status=live |url-access=subscription }}</ref>

The '''Endless Frontier Act''' was initially presented to senators [[Chuck Schumer]] (D-NY) and [[Todd Young]] (R-IN) by [[United States Under Secretary of State|Under Secretary of State]] [[Keith J. Krach|Keith Krach]] in October 2019, as part of the Global Economic Security Strategy to boost investment in high-tech research vital to U.S. national security.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 21, 2022 |title=Purdue Center for Tech Diplomacy Chairman Keith Krach and Director Bonnie Glick Counsel Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo on Securing Semiconductor Supply Chain |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20220321005892/en/Purdue-Center-for-Tech-Diplomacy-Chairman-Keith-Krach-and-Director-Bonnie-Glick-Counsel-Commerce-Secretary-Gina-Raimondo-on-Securing-Semiconductor-Supply-Chain |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=www.businesswire.com |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20220321005892/en/Purdue-Center-for-Tech-Diplomacy-Chairman-Keith-Krach-and-Director-Bonnie-Glick-Counsel-Commerce-Secretary-Gina-Raimondo-on-Securing-Semiconductor-Supply-Chain |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Krach">{{Cite web |last=Krach |first=Keith J.|authorlink=Keith J. Krach |date=June 17, 2021 |title=The Senate just passed the next Apollo program |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/technology/559065-the-senate-just-passed-the-next-apollo-program/ |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |language=en-US |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/technology/559065-the-senate-just-passed-the-next-apollo-program/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The plan was to grow $150&nbsp;billion in government R&D funding into a $500&nbsp;billion investment, with matching investments from the private sector and a coalition of technological allies dubbed the "Techno-Democracies-10" (TD-10).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Read @Kearney: The US–China high-tech competition is modernizing American industries: an interview with Keith Krach |url=https://www.kearney.com/technology/article/-/insights/the-us-china-high-tech-competition-is-modernizing-american-industries-an-interview-with-keith-krach |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=Kearney |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162801/https://www.kearney.com/technology/article/-/insights/the-us-china-high-tech-competition-is-modernizing-american-industries-an-interview-with-keith-krach |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Krach" /> On May 27, 2020, Young and Schumer, along with Congressmen [[Ro Khanna]] (D-CA) and [[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]] (R-WI.), introduced the bipartisan, bicameral '''Endless Frontier Act''' to solidify the United States' leadership in scientific and technological innovation through increased investments in the discovery, creation, and commercialization of technology fields of the future.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Young, Schumer Unveil Endless Frontier Act to Bolster U.S. Tech Leadership and Combat China {{!}} U.S. Senator Todd Young of Indiana |url=https://www.young.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/young-schumer-unveil-endless-frontier-act-to-bolster-us-tech-leadership-and-combat-china |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=www.young.senate.gov |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162756/https://www.young.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/young-schumer-unveil-endless-frontier-act-to-bolster-us-tech-leadership-and-combat-china |url-status=live }}</ref>

The '''[[United States Innovation and Competition Act]] of 2021 (USICA)''' (S. 1260), formerly known as the Endless Frontier Act, was United States legislation sponsored by Schumer and Young authorizing $110&nbsp;billion for basic and advanced technology research over a five-year period. Investment in basic and advanced research, commercialization, and education and training programs in [[artificial intelligence]], [[semiconductor]]s, [[quantum computing]], advanced communications, [[biotechnology]] and advanced energy, amounts to $100&nbsp;billion. Over $10&nbsp;billion was authorized for appropriation to designate ten regional technology hubs and create a [[supply chain crisis]]-response program.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Endless Frontier Act: Shifting the Focus from Defense to Offense |url=https://www.natlawreview.com/article/endless-frontier-act-shifting-focus-defense-to-offense |access-date=January 5, 2023 |website=[[The National Law Review]] |language=en |archive-date=May 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210513090302/https://www.natlawreview.com/article/endless-frontier-act-shifting-focus-defense-to-offense |url-status=live }}</ref>

The CHIPS for America Act portion stemmed from Krach and his team brokering the $12&nbsp;billion on-shoring of [[TSMC]] (Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company) to secure the supply chain of sophisticated semiconductors, on May 15, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ip |first=Greg |title='Industrial Policy' Is Back: The West Dusts Off Old Idea to Counter China |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/subsidies-chips-china-state-aid-biden-11627565906 |access-date=January 5, 2023 |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=July 29, 2021 |language=en-US |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://www.wsj.com/articles/subsidies-chips-china-state-aid-biden-11627565906 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Briefing with Under Secretary for Growth, Energy, and the Environment Keith Krach, Science and Technology Adviser to the Secretary Mung Chiang, and Assistant Secretary for International Security and Nonproliferation Christopher A. Ford On Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Corporation's Intent to Invest $12 Billion In the U.S. and on the CCP's Ability to Undermine U.S. Export Controls |url=https://2017-2021.state.gov/briefing-with-under-secretary-for-growth-energy-and-the-environment-keith-krach-science-and-technology-adviser-to-the-secretary-mung-chiang-and-assistant-secretary-for-international-security-and-n/ |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=United States Department of State |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=US woos Taiwan and its chipmakers in step toward trade pact |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/International-relations/US-China-tensions/US-woos-Taiwan-and-its-chipmakers-in-step-toward-trade-pact |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=Nikkei Asia |language=en-GB |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162759/https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/International-relations/US-China-tensions/US-woos-Taiwan-and-its-chipmakers-in-step-toward-trade-pact |url-status=live }}</ref> Krach's stated strategy was to use the [[TSMC]] announcement as a stimulus for fortifying a trusted supply chain by attracting TSMC's broad ecosystem of suppliers; persuading other chip companies to produce in U.S., especially Intel and Samsung; inspiring universities to develop engineering curricula focused on semiconductor manufacturing and designing a bipartisan bill (CHIPS for America) to provide the necessary funding.<ref name=":02">{{Cite web |last=Patterson |first=Alan |date=August 1, 2022 |title=Architect of CHIPS Act Speaks on Its Impact |url=https://www.eetimes.com/architect-of-chips-act-speaks-on-its-impact/ |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=EE Times |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162801/https://www.eetimes.com/architect-of-chips-act-speaks-on-its-impact/ |url-status=live }}</ref> This led to Krach and his team's close collaboration in creating the CHIPS for America component with senators [[John Cornyn]] (R-TX) and [[Mark Warner]] (D-VA).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Purdue Center for Tech Diplomacy Chairman Keith Krach and Director Bonnie Glick Counsel Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo on Securing Semiconductor Supply Chain |url=https://www.yahoo.com/now/purdue-center-tech-diplomacy-chairman-224100125.html |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=www.yahoo.com |language=en-US |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162756/https://www.yahoo.com/now/purdue-center-tech-diplomacy-chairman-224100125.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2020, Senator Warner joined U.S. senator [[John Cornyn]] in introducing the $52&nbsp;billion CHIPS for America Act.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hamblen |first=Matt |date=August 9, 2022 |title=President Biden signs CHIPS and Science Act: comments and reactions |language=en |work=Fierce Electronics |url=https://www.fierceelectronics.com/sensors/president-biden-signs-chips-and-science-act-comments-and-reactions |access-date=2023-01-05 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162759/https://www.fierceelectronics.com/sensors/president-biden-signs-chips-and-science-act-comments-and-reactions |url-status=live }}</ref> Elements of the [[Bioeconomy Research and Development Act]] of 2021 were also included.<ref>{{Cite web |title=How the CHIPS and Science Act Benefits Microbiology |url=https://asm.org/articles/policy/2022/aug2022/how-the-chips-and-science-act-benefits-microbiolog |access-date=2025-05-02 |website=ASM.org |language=en}}</ref>

Both bills were eventually merged into the [[United States Innovation and Competition Act|U.S. Innovation and Competition Act]] (USICA). On June 8, 2021, the USICA passed 68–32 in the Senate with bipartisan support. The House version of the Bill, [[America COMPETES Act#America COMPETES Act of 2022|America COMPETES Act of 2022]] (H.R. 4521), passed on February 4, 2022. The Senate passed an amended bill by substituting the text of H.R. 4521 with the text of the USICA on March 28, 2022. A Senate and House conference was required to reconcile the differences, which resulted in the bipartisan '''CHIPS and Science Act''', or "CHIPS Plus".<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 27, 2022 |title=The Bipartisan CHIPS Act—and a United U.S.— Are China's Biggest Fear |author-first1=Keith|author-last1=Krach|authorlink1=Kenneth J. Krach |url=https://www.newsweek.com/bipartisan-chips-act-united-us-are-chinas-biggest-fear-opinion-1728573 |access-date=January 5, 2023 |website=[[Newsweek]] |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162756/https://www.newsweek.com/bipartisan-chips-act-united-us-are-chinas-biggest-fear-opinion-1728573 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill passed the [[U.S. Senate]] by a vote of 64–33 on July 27, 2022.<ref name="Sprunt 1" /> On July 28, the $280 billion bill passed the [[U.S. House]] by a vote of 243–187–1.<ref name="verge-clears-congress"/> On August 1, 2022, the magazine ''[[EE Times]]'' (Electronic Engineering) dubbed Under Secretary of State [[Keith J. Krach|Keith Krach]] ({{as of|2023|02|lc=y}}, now the current Chairman of the Krach Institute for Tech Diplomacy at [[Purdue University]]) the architect of the CHIPS and Science Act.<ref name=":02" /> The bill was signed into law by President [[Joe Biden]] on August 9, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-08-09 |title=Remarks by President Biden at Signing of H.R. 4346, "The CHIPS and Science Act of 2022" |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2022/08/09/remarks-by-president-biden-at-signing-of-h-r-4346-the-chips-and-science-act-of-2022/ |access-date=2023-05-03 |publisher=[[The White House]] |language=en-US |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162759/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2022/08/09/remarks-by-president-biden-at-signing-of-h-r-4346-the-chips-and-science-act-of-2022/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Background and provisions ==
[[File:President Biden Delivers Remarks on the CHIPS and Science Act.webm|thumb|President [[Joe Biden]] delivers remarks on the CHIPS and Science Act at a [[semiconductor fabrication plant]] in [[Clay, New York]], April 25, 2024.]]
The law constitutes an industrial policy initiative which takes place against the background of a perceived [[Artificial Intelligence Cold War|AI Cold War]] between the US and China, as [[artificial intelligence]] technology relies on semiconductors.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Herman |first=Arthur |date=17 October 2022 |title=The Chip War With China Is Just Getting Started |work=Forbes |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/arthurherman/2022/10/17/the-chip-war-with-china-is-just-getting-started/?sh=4224c4346a08 |access-date=8 January 2023 |archive-date=January 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230108111903/https://www.forbes.com/sites/arthurherman/2022/10/17/the-chip-war-with-china-is-just-getting-started/?sh=4224c4346a08 |url-status=live }}</ref> The law was considered amidst a [[2020–present global chip shortage|global semiconductor shortage]] and intended to provide subsidies and tax credits to chip makers with operations in the United States. The [[U.S. Department of Commerce]] was granted the power to allocate funds based on companies' willingness to sustain research, build facilities, and train new workers.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Swanson |first=Ana |date=August 3, 2022 |title=Congress Is Giving Billions to the Chip Industry. Strings Are Attached. |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/03/business/economy/chip-industry-congress.html |url-access=subscription |access-date=August 5, 2022 |archive-date=October 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221021051739/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/03/business/economy/chip-industry-congress.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

For semiconductor and telecommunications purposes, the CHIPS Act designates roughly $106&nbsp;billion. The CHIPS Act includes $39&nbsp;billion in tax benefits, loan guarantees and grants, administered by the DOC to encourage American companies to build new chip manufacturing plants in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web |title=What's in the recently passed CHIPS Act? |url=https://usafacts.org/articles/whats-in-the-recently-passed-chips-act/ |access-date=2022-08-15 |website=USAFacts |language=en |archive-date=October 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221015070104/https://usafacts.org/articles/whats-in-the-recently-passed-chips-act/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, $11&nbsp;billion would go toward advanced semiconductor research and development, separable into $8.5&nbsp;billion of that total going to the [[National Institute for Standards and Technology]], $500&nbsp;million to [[Manufacturing USA]], and $2&nbsp;billion to a new public research hub called the National Semiconductor Technology Center. $24&nbsp;billion would go to a new 25 percent advanced semiconductor manufacturing tax credit to encourage firms to stay in the United States, and $200&nbsp;million would go to the [[National Science Foundation]] to resolve short-term labor supply issues.<ref name="McKinsey 2022" /><ref name="CSIS 2022" />

According to [[McKinsey]], "The CHIPS Act allocates $2 billion to the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] to fund microelectronics research, fabrication, and workforce training. An additional $500 million goes to the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] to coordinate with foreign-government partners on semiconductor supply chain security. And $1.5 billion funds the USA Telecommunications Act of 2020, which aims to enhance competitiveness of software and hardware supply chains of open [[radio access network|RAN]] [[5G]] networks."<ref name="McKinsey 2022">{{Cite web |last1=Badlam |first1=Justin |last2=Clark |first2=Stephen |last3=Gajendragakar |first3=Suhrid |last4=Kumar |first4=Adi |last5=O'Rourke |first5=Sara |last6=Swartz |first6=Dale |date=October 4, 2022 |title=The CHIPS and Science Act: Here's what's in it |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/public-and-social-sector/our-insights/the-chips-and-science-act-heres-whats-in-it |access-date=October 5, 2022 |website=McKinsey & Company |archive-date=October 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005070010/https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/public-and-social-sector/our-insights/the-chips-and-science-act-heres-whats-in-it |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="CSIS 2022">{{Cite journal |last1=Kersten |first1=Alexander |last2=Athanasia |first2=Gabrielle |last3=Arcuri |first3=Gregory |date=August 9, 2022 |title=A Look at the CHIPS-Related Portions of CHIPS+ |url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/look-chips-related-portions-chips |access-date=October 5, 2022 |website=Center for Strategic and International Studies |archive-date=October 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005151524/https://www.csis.org/analysis/look-chips-related-portions-chips |url-status=live }}</ref> (The open RAN research innovation fund is controlled by the [[National Telecommunications and Information Administration]].)<ref name="National Telecommunications and Information Administration Open RAN 2024">{{cite web | title=Public Wireless Supply Chain Innovation Fund | publisher=National Telecommunications and Information Administration | date=February 12, 2024 | url=https://www.ntia.gov/page/innovation-fund | access-date=April 30, 2024}}</ref> Companies are subjected to a 10-year ban prohibiting them from producing chips more advanced than [[28 nm process|28 nanometers]] in China and Russia if they are awarded subsidies under the law.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Debby |last1=Wu |first2=Daniel |last2=Flatley |first3=Jenny |last3=Leonard |date=August 2, 2022 |title=US to Stop TSMC, Intel From Adding Advanced Chip Fabs in China |work=[[Bloomberg, L.P.|Bloomberg]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-02/us-to-stop-tsmc-intel-from-adding-advanced-chip-fabs-in-china |access-date=August 13, 2022 |archive-date=May 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230503215915/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-02/us-to-stop-tsmc-intel-from-adding-advanced-chip-fabs-in-china |url-status=live }}</ref>

The law authorizes $174&nbsp;billion for uses other than semiconductor and telecom technologies.<ref name="McKinsey 2022" /><ref name="CSIS 2 2022" /> It authorizes, but does not appropriate, extended [[NASA]] funding for the [[International Space Station]] to 2030, partially funds the [[Artemis program]] returning humans to the Moon, and directs NASA to establish a Moon to Mars Program Office for a [[human mission to Mars]] beyond the Artemis program. The law also obligates NASA to perform research into further domesticating its supply chains and diversifying and developing its workforce, reducing the [[environmental effects of aviation]], integrating [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] detection with [[air traffic control]], investigating [[nuclear propulsion]] for spacecraft, continuing the [[search for extraterrestrial intelligence]] and [[xenology]] efforts, and boosting [[astronomical survey]]s for [[Near-Earth object]]s including the [[NEO Surveyor]] project.<ref name="Politico 20220809" /><ref name="Errick 2022">{{Cite web |last=Errick |first=Kirsten |date=August 4, 2022 |title=NASA Authorization Act Aims to Strengthen U.S. Space Exploration |url=https://www.nextgov.com/emerging-tech/2022/08/nasa-authorization-act-aims-strengthen-us-space-exploration/375394/ |access-date=August 24, 2022 |website=Nextgov.com |archive-date=August 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220824021158/https://www.nextgov.com/emerging-tech/2022/08/nasa-authorization-act-aims-strengthen-us-space-exploration/375394/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The law could potentially invest $67&nbsp;billion in accelerating advanced zero-emissions technologies (such as improved [[energy storage]], [[hydrogen economy]] technologies, and [[carbon capture and storage]]) to mass markets, advancing building efficiency, and improving [[climate science]] research, according to the climate action think tank [[Rocky Mountain Institute]]. The law would invest $81&nbsp;billion in the NSF, including new money for [[STEM]] education (it recommends $100 million in rural schools, a 50 percent increase in Noyce Teaching Scholarships, and $300 million in a "STEM Teacher Corps")<ref name="AIP 2022">{{cite web |last=Peterson|first=Andrea|title=Workforce Diversity Initiatives in the CHIPS and Science Act | website=AIP | date=September 16, 2022 | url=https://ww2.aip.org/fyi/2022/workforce-diversity-initiatives-chips-and-science-act | access-date=April 28, 2024}}</ref> and defense against foreign [[intellectual property infringement]], and $20&nbsp;billion in the new Directorate for Technology, Innovation, and Partnerships, which would be tasked with deploying the above technologies as well as promoting social and ethical considerations, and authorizes but does not appropriate $12&nbsp;billion for [[ARPA-E]].<ref name="Atlantic 20220810">{{Cite web |last=Meyer |first=Robinson |date=August 10, 2022 |title=Congress Just Passed a Big Climate Bill. No, Not That One. |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/08/chips-act-climate-bill-biden/671095/ |access-date=October 5, 2022 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |archive-date=October 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005151524/https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/08/chips-act-climate-bill-biden/671095/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Guston 2023"/>  For the [[United States Department of Energy]] the law creates a new [[501(c)(3) organization]], the '''Foundation for Energy Security and Innovation''', to leverage [[philanthropy in the United States|philanthropy]] for improving the workforce and bolstering energy research.<ref name="DOE FESI announcement">{{cite web | title=Agency-Related Foundation Will Propel DOE to New Heights | website=Energy.gov | date=February 9, 2023 | url=https://www.energy.gov/technologytransitions/articles/agency-related-foundation-will-propel-doe-new-heights | access-date=July 31, 2024}}</ref> It contains annual DOE budget increases for other purposes including [[supercomputer]], [[nuclear fusion]] and [[particle accelerator]] research as well as [[minority-serving institution]] outreach and workforce development for teachers, and directs the DOC to establish $10&nbsp;billion worth of research hubs in post-industrial rural and urban communities that have been subjected to historical underinvestment.<ref name="McKinsey 2022" /><ref name="CSIS 2 2022">{{Cite journal |last1=Arcuri |first1=Gregory |last2=Shivakumar |first2=Sujai |date=August 11, 2022 |title=A Look at the Science-Related Portions of CHIPS+ |url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/look-science-related-portions-chips |access-date=October 5, 2022 |website=Center for Strategic and International Studies |archive-date=October 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005151534/https://www.csis.org/analysis/look-science-related-portions-chips |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="AIP 2022"/><ref name="Ross Muro 2024">{{cite web |last1=Ross|first1=Martha|last2=Muro|first2=Mark|title=How federal, state, and local leaders can leverage the CHIPS and Science Act as a landmark workforce opportunity | website=Brookings | date=January 31, 2024 | url=https://www.brookings.edu/articles/how-federal-state-and-local-leaders-can-leverage-the-chips-and-science-act-as-a-landmark-workforce-opportunity/ | access-date=April 28, 2024}}</ref>

As a national security law, the law contains a variety of provisions related to research ethics, foreign talent recruitment, restrictions on [[Confucius Institute]]s, and establishing new research security initiatives in the DOE, NIST, and the NSF.<ref name="AAU 2022">{{cite web | title=CHIPS and Science Act Summary of Research Security Provisions | website=Association of American Universities (AAU) | date=September 9, 2022 | url=https://www.aau.edu/sites/default/files/AAU-Files/Key-Issues/Science-Security/CHIPSandScienceFinalResearchSecurityProvisions.pdf | access-date=April 28, 2024}}</ref>

The law makes extensive recommendations to the NSF to add social, legal, and ethical considerations to the award process in all of its research activities, hinting at an embrace of [[technology assessment#Forms and concepts of technology assessment|public participatory technology assessment]]; the law does ''not'' invoke an NSF doctrine called the "broader impacts criterion" to do so.<ref name="Guston 2023">{{cite web |author1-link=David H. Guston | last=Guston | first=David | title=Making the Most of the "Ethical and Societal Considerations" in the CHIPS and Science Act | website=Issues in Science and Technology | date=May 4, 2023 | url=https://issues.org/ethical-societal-considerations-nsf-guston/ | access-date=April 28, 2024}}</ref> The law invests roughly $90 billion in strengthening and diversifying the STEM workforce through 33 programs, many of them incorporated deeply in the aforementioned semiconductor incentive, NSF labor supply, Tech Hubs, and DoD microelectronics R&D efforts; beyond those, the law authorizes $2.8 billion for standalone education projects, creates a Chief Diversity Officer position and codifies the [[Eddie Bernice Johnson]] INCLUDES Network to serve as the NSF's main [[diversity, equity, and inclusion]] program. The law expands NSF demographic data collection and workplace inclusion efforts, and help to grantees in caregiver roles and the fight against sexual harassment.<ref name="AIP 2022"/> The law emphasizes skilled technical jobs that do not require a bachelor's degree, and directs grant applicants to closely integrate workforce initiatives with job training; notably, it does ''not'' invest in the [[United States Department of Labor]] to carry this out.<ref name="AIP 2022"/><ref name="Ross Muro 2024"/>

