Every senator in the [[Senate Democratic Caucus]] except for [[Bernie Sanders]] voted in favor of passing the CHIPS Act, and they were joined by seventeen Republican senators, including Senate Republican leader [[Mitch McConnell]], Utah senator [[Mitt Romney]], and South Carolina senator [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref name="Sprunt 1">{{Cite news |last=Sprunt |first=Barbara |date=July 27, 2022 |title=Legislation to subsidize U.S.-made semiconductor chips heads to Biden's desk |work=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/07/26/1113470753/chip-production-semiconductor-senate |access-date=May 3, 2023 |archive-date=October 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221024101503/https://www.npr.org/2022/07/26/1113470753/chip-production-semiconductor-senate |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Reception ==

=== Support ===
Many legislators and elected officials from across both the federal government and various state governments endorsed the passage. A large group of governors consisting of Pennsylvania's [[Tom Wolf]], Alabama's [[Kay Ivey]], California's [[Gavin Newsom]], Kentucky's [[Andy Beshear]], Michigan's [[Gretchen Whitmer]], Wisconsin's [[Tony Evers]], Illinois' [[J. B. Pritzker]], Kansas' [[Laura Kelly]], and North Carolina's [[Roy Cooper]] pushed for the passage of the bill back in November 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 10, 2021 |title=Governor Wolf, Bipartisan Governors Urge Congress to Pass CHIPS Act to Create American Jobs, Boost Semiconductor Production |url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/newsroom/governor-wolf-bipartisan-governors-urge-congress-to-pass-chips-act-to-create-american-jobs-boost-semiconductor-production/ |access-date=2022-08-11 |website=Governor Tom Wolf |language=en-US |archive-date=June 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220629103852/https://www.governor.pa.gov/newsroom/governor-wolf-bipartisan-governors-urge-congress-to-pass-chips-act-to-create-american-jobs-boost-semiconductor-production/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Governors urge passage of CHIPS Act funding to spur semiconductor 're-shoring' {{!}} InsideTrade.com |url=https://insidetrade.com/daily-news/governors-urge-passage-chips-act-funding-spur-semiconductor-%E2%80%98re-shoring%E2%80%99 |access-date=2022-08-11 |website=insidetrade.com |archive-date=August 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220811003715/https://insidetrade.com/daily-news/governors-urge-passage-chips-act-funding-spur-semiconductor-%E2%80%98re-shoring%E2%80%99 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Separately, Ohio governor [[Mike DeWine]], whose state became the home of [[Intel]]'s newest [[semiconductor fabrication plant]] in the [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] suburb of [[New Albany, Ohio|New Albany]], as well as Texas governor [[Greg Abbott]] and Texas senator [[John Cornyn]], whose state was the home of a major investment from [[Samsung]], each pushed for the bill to be passed and applauded its advancement through Congress.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 28, 2022 |title=Congress passes CHIPS Act, paving way for microchip plant in Ohio |url=https://www.news5cleveland.com/news/state/congresss-passage-of-chips-act-paves-way-for-intels-microchip-plant-in-ohio |access-date=2022-08-11 |website=WEWS |language=en |archive-date=August 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220807235714/https://www.news5cleveland.com/news/state/congresss-passage-of-chips-act-paves-way-for-intels-microchip-plant-in-ohio |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=BeMiller |first=Haley |title=Intel CEO: Company moving 'full speed ahead' on Ohio plans after CHIPS Act passes Congress |url=https://www.dispatch.com/story/news/2022/07/28/chips-act-four-ohio-republicans-boost-bill-pushed-intel/10176845002/ |access-date=2022-08-11 |website=The Columbus Dispatch |language=en-US |archive-date=August 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220809162258/https://www.dispatch.com/story/news/2022/07/28/chips-act-four-ohio-republicans-boost-bill-pushed-intel/10176845002/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Moneyhon |first=Carl H. |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/anb/9780198606697.article.0400249 |title=Coke, Richard (1829–1897), governor of Texas and U.S. senator |date=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |series=American National Biography Online |doi=10.1093/anb/9780198606697.article.0400249 |access-date=August 11, 2022 |archive-date=May 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230503215915/https://www.anb.org/display/10.1093/anb/9780198606697.001.0001/anb-9780198606697-e-0400249;jsessionid=28781C970EBA7533188AB63465FC41D1 |url-status=live }}</ref> It has received widespread support from chip firms, though they were concerned about the provision banning them from further investments in China.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Nellis |first=Stephen |date=July 20, 2022 |title=Chip designers warm to U.S. bill despite big benefits to Intel |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/us-chip-industry-split-over-chips-act-benefits-intel-sources-2022-07-18/ |access-date=August 5, 2022 |archive-date=October 12, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221012210829/https://www.reuters.com/technology/us-chip-industry-split-over-chips-act-benefits-intel-sources-2022-07-18/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Cheng Ting-Fang |last2=Lauly Li |last3=Yifan Yu |date=August 2, 2022 |title=CHIPS Act leaves chipmakers facing choice between U.S. and China |work=NIKKEI Asia |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Tech/Semiconductors/CHIPS-Act-leaves-chipmakers-facing-choice-between-U.S.-and-China |access-date=August 5, 2022 |archive-date=October 19, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221019180945/https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Tech/Semiconductors/CHIPS-Act-leaves-chipmakers-facing-choice-between-U.S.-and-China |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Intel]]'s then-CEO [[Pat Gelsinger]] said during an earnings call on September 30, 2022, that CHIPS Act subsidies were leading the company to explore building empty fab buildings (known as a "shell-first strategy") and aggressively acquire smaller competitors before installing any equipment, to avoid contributing to a predicted semiconductor glut.<ref name="Intel end of Q3 2022 investor call">{{Cite web |last=Motley Fool Transcribing |date=October 28, 2022 |title=Intel (INTC) Q3 2022 Earnings Call Transcript |url=https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2022/10/27/intel-intc-q3-2022-earnings-call-transcript/ |access-date=March 1, 2023 |website=The Motley Fool |archive-date=March 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230301044729/https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2022/10/27/intel-intc-q3-2022-earnings-call-transcript/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Harris Feb282023" />

=== Opposition ===
The bill was criticized by Republican House leader [[Kevin McCarthy]] and senator [[Bernie Sanders]] as a "blank check", which the latter equated to a bribe to semiconductor companies.<ref name="Sprunt 1" /><ref name="verge-clears-congress">{{Cite news |last=Kelly |first=Makena |date=July 28, 2022 |title=CHIPS Act clears Congress, ensuring $52 billion boost to US foundries |work=[[The Verge]] |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/28/23282494/semiconductors-chips-and-science-act-joe-biden-congress-nvidia |access-date=August 5, 2022 |archive-date=September 1, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220901231113/https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/28/23282494/semiconductors-chips-and-science-act-joe-biden-congress-nvidia |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=NEWS: Sanders Opposes All Blank Checks to Chip Companies » Senator Bernie Sanders |url=https://www.sanders.senate.gov/press-releases/news-sanders-opposes-all-blank-checks-to-chip-companies/ |access-date=2022-09-09 |website=Senator Bernie Sanders |language=en-US |archive-date=September 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220909122507/https://www.sanders.senate.gov/press-releases/news-sanders-opposes-all-blank-checks-to-chip-companies/ |url-status=live }}</ref> China lobbied against the bill and criticized it as being "reminiscent of a 'Cold War mentality{{'"}}.<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Meara |first=Sean |date=July 29, 2022 |title=China Says US Chip Act Will Harm Supply Chain, Global Trade |url=https://www.asiafinancial.com/china-says-us-chip-act-will-harm-supply-chain-global-trade |access-date=2022-08-09 |website=Asia Financial |language=en-US |archive-date=August 25, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220825201518/https://www.asiafinancial.com/china-says-us-chip-act-will-harm-supply-chain-global-trade |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Concerns of protectionism ===
In a piece for the [[Brookings Institution]] on December 20, 2022, [[Sarah Kreps]] and Paul Timmers expressed concerns regarding the protectionist provisions of the CHIPS and Science Act and the risk of a subsidy race with the [[EU]], which proposed its own [[European Chips Act]] in 2022.<ref name="Brookings">{{Cite news |last1=Timmers |first1=Paul |last2=Kreps |first2=Sarah |date=20 December 2022 |title=Bringing economics back into EU and U.S. chips policy |work=Brookings |url=https://www.brookings.edu/techstream/bringing-economics-back-into-the-politics-of-the-eu-and-u-s-chips-acts-china-semiconductor-competition/ |access-date=8 January 2023 |archive-date=January 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230108121604/https://www.brookings.edu/techstream/bringing-economics-back-into-the-politics-of-the-eu-and-u-s-chips-acts-china-semiconductor-competition/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Concerns of poor workforce development===
In a piece for Brookings on May 25, 2023, Annelies Goger and Banu Ozkazanc-Pan found the Act was vague in many of its workforce development provisions, and criticized the statute for failing to offer a comprehensive, 'wraparound' approach to workforce development. They focused on its lack of supportive provisions for closing racial and gender gaps in STEM, its lack of requirements for equitable access to child care and non-academic mentorship programs beyond well-resourced communities, and its piecemeal approach to the innovation cycle.<ref name="Goger Ozkazanc-Pan 2023">{{cite web |first1=Annelies |last1=Goger|first2=Banu|last2=Ozkazanc-Pan|title=The CHIPS and Science Act won't build inclusive innovation ecosystems on its own | website=Brookings | date=May 25, 2023 | url=https://www.brookings.edu/articles/the-chips-and-science-act-wont-build-inclusive-innovation-ecosystems-on-its-own/ | access-date=April 27, 2024}}</ref> Seven months later, Brookings staffers Martha Ross and Mark Muro also said the act's workforce provisions reflected a fragmented approach and their costs were difficult to determine.<ref name="Ross Muro 2024"/> The Department of Commerce's Office of the Inspector General criticized the CHIPS Program and R&D Offices in particular for not crafting a plan for their own workforce development, though the OIG did note that they exceeded their hiring goals due to optimizing for speed and meeting national security goals.<ref>{{cite report |author=<!-- not stated --> |date=May 20, 2024 |title=NIST Surpassed Hiring Goals for CHIPS But Did Not Develop a Comprehensive Workforce Plan  |url=https://www.oig.doc.gov/wp-content/OIGPublications/OIG-24-023-I-SECURED.pdf |location=Washington, DC |publisher=U.S. Department of Commerce, Office of Inspector General |docket=OIG-24-023-I |access-date=November 27, 2025}}</ref><ref name="Meyers 2025">{{cite web | last=Meyers | first=Sara | title=Hiring: Damned If You Do, Damned If You Don't | website=Factory Settings | date=November 25, 2025 | url=https://www.factorysettings.org/p/hiring-damned-if-you-do-damned-if | access-date=November 27, 2025}}</ref>

===Environmental concerns===
Writing in the Substack climate and finance newsletter ''The Gigaton'', Stanford MBA students Georgia Carroll and Zac Maslia criticized the Act for lacking incentives to add [[renewable energy]] to chipmakers' [[base load]]s, and [[reclaimed water]] and [[Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances|PFAS]] alternatives to their material inputs, and noted the extensive environmental impact of the chipmaker and data center industry was at odds with the output from the new research programs of the Act.<ref name="Gigaton 2024">{{cite web | last1=Carroll | first1=Georgia |last2=Maslia|first2=Zac | title=CHIPS Act: The Climate Consequences of a Growing Demand for Semiconductors | website=Substack | date=May 2, 2024 | url=https://thegigaton.substack.com/p/chips-act-the-climate-consequences| access-date=May 2, 2024}}</ref>

===Concerns of inaction on unions, stock buybacks===
[[Robert Kuttner]], [[economic nationalist]] commentator and editor of ''[[The American Prospect]]'', expressed concerns that the bill did not provide enough resources to allow local residents near fabs to organize or form a [[trade union]] (thereby making unions rely too heavily on [[community benefits agreement]]s compared to federal policy), that the Commerce Department would be too friendly to states with [[right-to-work law]]s (where the first new fabs would be built), that the bill did not restrictively define a "domestic company" regarding financing, and that fab owners would simply use CHIPS Act money to [[Share repurchase|buy back stocks]].<ref name="Kuttner 2023">{{Cite web |last=Kuttner |first=Robert |date=January 24, 2023 |title=Reclaiming U.S. Industry |url=https://prospect.org/economy/2023-01-24-biden-american-industrial-policy/ |access-date=February 22, 2023 |website=The American Prospect |archive-date=February 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230203113154/https://prospect.org/economy/2023-01-24-biden-american-industrial-policy/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In response to these concerns, on February 28, 2023, [[United States Secretary of Commerce]] [[Gina Raimondo]] published the first application for CHIPS Act grants, which encourages fab operators to use [[Project Labor Agreement]]s for facilitating union negotiations during construction, outline their plans to curtail stock buybacks, share excess profits with the federal government, and open or point out nearby [[child care]] facilities.<ref name="The New York Times 2023">{{Cite web |last1=Tankersley |first1=Jim |last2=Swanson |first2=Jim |date=February 27, 2023 |title=Biden's Semiconductor Plan Flexes the Power of the Federal Government |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/27/us/politics/chips-act-biden-commerce-department.html |access-date=March 1, 2023 |website=The New York Times |archive-date=February 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230228235312/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/27/us/politics/chips-act-biden-commerce-department.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Harris Feb282023">{{Cite web |last=Harris |first=Lee |date=February 28, 2023 |title=Harris on TAP: Unions for On-Time Construction |url=https://prospect.org/blogs-and-newsletters/tap/2023-02-28-commerce-semiconductor-construction-labor/ |access-date=March 1, 2023 |website=The American Prospect |archive-date=March 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230301070502/https://prospect.org/blogs-and-newsletters/tap/2023-02-28-commerce-semiconductor-construction-labor/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Harris Jun222023"/> The application led to over 200 statements of interest from private companies within the first month and a half, looking to invest across the entire semiconductor supply chain in 35 states;<ref name="U.S. Department of Commerce 2023">{{cite web | title=CHIPS for America's Strong Start | website=U.S. Department of Commerce | date=April 13, 2023 | url=https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/USDOC/bulletins/354ebdf | access-date=May 26, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Dayen 2023"/> by June 2023, the number had reached over 300.<ref name="Lee Nellis 2023">{{cite web | last1=Lee | first1=Jane|last2=Nellis |first2=Stephen| title=Applied Materials to invest $4 bln in Silicon Valley chip research center | website=Reuters | date=May 22, 2023 | url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/applied-materials-invest-4-bln-silicon-valley-chip-research-center-2023-05-22/ | access-date=June 24, 2023}}</ref> The ''Prospect'' later covered the lack of progress in PLA talks between key investor [[TSMC]] and local unions in Phoenix, and included both author Lee Harris's claim that the Raimondo guidance was insufficient in helping the talks, and liberal commentator [[Ezra Klein]]'s criticism of the Raimondo guidance as excessive.<ref name="Harris Apr72023">{{Cite web |last=Harris |first=Lee |date=April 7, 2023 |title=BASED: CHIPS Act Manufacturer Snubs Union Workers |url=https://americanprospect.bluelena.io/index.php?action=social&chash=cb79f8fa58b91d3af6c9c991f63962d3.1990 |access-date=April 7, 2023 |website=The American Prospect |archive-date=April 7, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407154116/https://americanprospect.bluelena.io/index.php?action=social&chash=cb79f8fa58b91d3af6c9c991f63962d3.1990 |url-status=live }}</ref> Harris later reported that as a consequence TSMC and its non-union subcontractors had routinely engaged in alleged wage theft, underreported safety violations, and cut out various installation procedures that would have prevented costly repairs, delaying its projects.<ref name="Harris Jun222023">{{cite web | last=Harris | first=Lee | title=Chipmaker's Scramble to Build Marred by Mistakes and Injuries | website=The American Prospect | date=June 22, 2023 | url=https://prospect.org/labor/2023-06-22-tsmc-semiconductor-factory-phoenix-accidents/ | access-date=June 24, 2023}}</ref>

===Antitrust concerns===
In February 2024, the antitrust think tank [[American Economic Liberties Project]] released a report evaluating the state of the semiconductor industry after the CHIPS and Science Act passed. It found that the Act was insufficient in dealing with what it saw as the effective [[monopolization]] and [[monopsony]] of the American semiconductor industry by TSMC and by '[[fabless]]' semiconductor firms that practiced routine outsourcing, such as [[Nvidia]] and [[Apple Inc.]], the result of shareholder-driven decisions. It also found the Act was insufficient in shoring up American mid-level, consumer market-oriented manufacturing by increasing competition and resiliency there. It recommended that the Commerce Department increasingly involve the [[Federal Trade Commission]] and other antitrust agencies in its decision-making, incubate four mid-size competitors to TSMC, require 'fabless' firms to double their source numbers, and strategically levy [[tariff]]s and fees on select consumer electronics deemed lacking in American sourcing.<ref name="Achilles Peinert Rangel 2024">{{cite web | last1=Achilles | first1=Todd | last2=Peinert | first2=Erik | last3=Rangel | first3=Daniel | title=Reshoring and Restoring: CHIPS Implementation for a Competitive Semiconductor Industry | website=American Economic Liberties Project | date=February 6, 2024 | url=https://www.economicliberties.us/our-work/reshoring-and-restoring-chips-implementation-for-a-competitive-semiconductor-industry/ | access-date=March 17, 2024}}</ref>

== Impact ==
[[File:P20221206AS-1047 (52651362655).jpg|thumb|President Biden taking a selfie with construction workers at a TSMC plant in Arizona, December 2022]]

===Science impact===
{{Expand section|small=no|find=impact of CHIPS and Science Act on basic research -semiconductors|with=some examples of research projects benefiting from the act, beyond semiconductors and telecom|date=April 2024}}
In August 2023, around the one-year anniversary of the act becoming law, the NSF released a fact sheet outlining what it had done in the first year. Notably, the Technology, Innovation and Partnerships Directorate had awarded more than 760 grants and signed 18 contracts in research and development, and incentivized $4 billion in private capital and 35 exits from federal seed funding for private companies; the NSF issued two letters to employees on research security, increased STEM scholarship amounts, and created a National Secure Data Service per the act's directives.<ref name="NSF CHIPS fact sheet 2023">{{cite web | title=Celebrating One Year of 'CHIPS and Science'| website=NSF – National Science Foundation | date=August 4, 2023 | url=https://nsf-gov-resources.nsf.gov/2023-08/NSF%20CHIPS_and_Science_1_year_fact_sheet.pdf | access-date=April 29, 2024}}</ref> The DOE also issued a press release to commemorate the anniversary, noting materials science, quantum computing and biotechnology had received major attention from the act, as well as efforts to improve energy use, materials sourcing transparency and recycling of computer chips.<ref name="Energy.gov 2023 anniversary press release">{{cite web |last=Bui|first=Vivien| title=The CHIPS and Science Act: A Game-Changer in its First Year | website=Energy.gov | date=August 10, 2023 | url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/chips-and-science-act-game-changer-its-first-year | access-date=April 29, 2024}}</ref>

On the second anniversary of the Act becoming law, the NSF put out an updated fact sheet. The TIP Directorate had now awarded a two-year total of 2,455 grants and signed 25 contracts in research and development, and incentivized $8.15 billion in private capital and more than 75 exits from federal seed funding; the NSF also designated 10 new Regional Innovation Engines in January 2024, issued the first 40 awards in the ExLENT program promoting [[experiential learning]] in semiconductor engineering at universities, launched the NSF SBIR/SBTT Fast-Track pilot program for certain startups and the APTO program promoting technology prediction, and signed a memorandum of understanding with the Commerce Department for further action in workforce development.<ref name="NSF 2024">{{cite web |last1=Gianchandani|first1=Erwin|last2=Narcho|first2=Gracie | title=Celebrating the 2nd anniversary of the 'CHIPS and Science Act of 2022' | website=NSF – National Science Foundation | date=August 13, 2024 | url=https://new.nsf.gov/tip/updates/celebrating-2nd-anniversary-chips-science-act-2022 | access-date=September 12, 2024}}</ref>

In September 2024, the [[National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine]] produced a report on NASA's organizational efficiency mandated by the law,<ref>{{USCode|51|20113}}, {{USStat|136|1754}}</ref> which found several critical weaknesses, namely, in long-term planning, workforce retention, headquarters staffing levels, budgetary support from Congress, aging infrastructure, and emphasis on research and development as part of instrument planning.<ref name="NASEM report on NASA infrastructure">{{cite book | author=Committee on NASA Mission Critical Workforce, Infrastructure, and Technology | author2=Aeronautics and Space Engineering Board | author3=Space Studies Board | author4=Division on Engineering and Physical Sciences | author5=National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine | title=NASA at a Crossroads: Maintaining Workforce, Infrastructure, and Technology Preeminence in the Coming Decades | publisher=National Academies Press | publication-place=Washington, D.C. | date=2024 | isbn=978-0-309-71631-4 | doi=10.17226/27519 }}</ref>

===Project announcements===
Many companies and ecosystem suppliers have announced investment plans since May 2020, when TSMC announced that it would build a fab in Arizona,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Krach |first1=Keith |last2=Hormats |first2=Bob |date=December 21, 2022 |title=Funding the CHIPS and Science Act is a national security imperative |url=https://thehill.com/opinion/technology/3782796-funding-the-chips-and-science-act-is-a-national-security-imperative/ |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=The Hill |language=en-US |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162756/https://thehill.com/opinion/technology/3782796-funding-the-chips-and-science-act-is-a-national-security-imperative/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":02" /><ref name="Conness 2023" /><ref name="Ravi Casanova 2022" /> which upon completion began producing [[Apple A16]] chips in earnest in mid-September 2024, according to independent journalist Tim Culpan,<ref name="Culpan 2024">{{cite web | last=Culpan | first=Tim | title=Apple Mobile Processors Are Now Made in America. By TSMC | website=Substack | date=September 17, 2024 | url=https://timculpan.substack.com/p/apple-mobile-processors-are-now-made | access-date=October 22, 2024}}</ref> achieving 4 percent higher production yields than the average in Taiwan by late October.<ref name="Bloomberg TSMC yields">{{cite web | last=Hawkins | first=Mackenzie | title=TSMC's Arizona Chip Production Yields Surpass Taiwan's in Win for US Push | website=Bloomberg.com | date=October 24, 2024 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-10-24/tsmc-s-arizona-chip-production-yields-surpass-taiwan-s-a-win-for-us-push | access-date=November 4, 2024}}</ref>

These include (before the act passed on August 9, 2022):

* In July 2021, [[GlobalFoundries]] announced plans to build a new $1&nbsp;billion [[Semiconductor fabrication plant|fab]] in Upstate New York.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=GlobalFoundries Plans to Build New Fab in Upstate New York in Private-Public Partnership to Support U.S. Semiconductor Manufacturing |date=July 19, 2021 |publisher=GlobalFoundries |url=https://investors.gf.com/news-releases/news-release-details/globalfoundries-plans-build-new-fab-upstate-new-york-private |access-date=2023-01-05 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162812/https://investors.gf.com/news-releases/news-release-details/globalfoundries-plans-build-new-fab-upstate-new-york-private |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In November 2021, [[Samsung]] announced plans to build a $17&nbsp;billion semiconductor factory to begin operations in the second half of 2024. It is the largest foreign direct investment ever in the state of Texas.<ref>{{Cite news |date=November 24, 2021 |title=Samsung says it will build $17B chip factory in Texas |language=en |work=NPR |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.npr.org/2021/11/24/1058770506/samsung-says-it-will-build-17b-chip-factory-in-texas |access-date=2023-01-05 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://www.npr.org/2021/11/24/1058770506/samsung-says-it-will-build-17b-chip-factory-in-texas |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In January 2022, Intel announced an initial $20&nbsp;billion investment that will generate 3,000 jobs, the largest investment in Ohio's history, with plans to grow to $100&nbsp;billion investment in eight fabrication plants.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Intel to invest up to $100 billion in Ohio chip plants |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/21/intel-plans-20-billion-chip-manufacturing-site-in-ohio.html |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=CNBC |date=January 21, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/21/intel-plans-20-billion-chip-manufacturing-site-in-ohio.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In May 2022, [[Purdue University]] launched the nation's first comprehensive semiconductor degrees program in anticipation of the CHIPS Act spurring the creation of jobs for 50,000 trained semiconductor engineers in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Service |first=Purdue News |title=Purdue launches nation's first comprehensive Semiconductor Degrees Program |url=https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2022/Q2/purdue-launches-nations-first-comprehensive-semiconductor-degrees-program.html |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=www.purdue.edu |date=May 27, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162758/https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2022/Q2/purdue-launches-nations-first-comprehensive-semiconductor-degrees-program.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Paul |first=Joseph |title=Purdue launches nation's first semiconductor degree program |url=https://www.wlfi.com/news/purdue-launches-nations-first-semiconductor-degree-program/article_e2e3ccac-ddf3-11ec-a80c-478643b0c0f6.html |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=WLFI News 18 |date=May 27, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162755/https://www.wlfi.com/news/purdue-launches-nations-first-semiconductor-degree-program/article_e2e3ccac-ddf3-11ec-a80c-478643b0c0f6.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In May 2022, [[Texas Instruments]] broke ground on new 300-mm semiconductor wafer fabrication plants in Sherman, Texas, and projected its investments will reach $30&nbsp;billion and create as many as 3,000 jobs.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 20, 2022 |title=Texas Instruments Breaks Ground on New 300mm Semiconductor Wafer Fabrication Plant in Sherman, Texas |url=https://www.semiconductor-digest.com/texas-instruments-breaks-ground-on-new-300mm-semiconductor-wafer-fabrication-plant-in-sherman-texas/ |access-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162757/https://www.semiconductor-digest.com/texas-instruments-breaks-ground-on-new-300mm-semiconductor-wafer-fabrication-plant-in-sherman-texas/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In July 2022, [[SkyWater Technology|SkyWater]] announced plans to build an advanced $1.8&nbsp;billion semiconductor manufacturing facility with the government of [[Indiana]] and Purdue University to pursue CHIPS funding.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lee |first=Jane Lanhee |date=July 20, 2022 |title=SkyWater unveils plans to build $1.8 bln chip facility in Indiana |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/skywater-unveils-plans-build-18-bln-chip-facility-indiana-2022-07-20/ |access-date=2023-01-05 |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162756/https://www.reuters.com/technology/skywater-unveils-plans-build-18-bln-chip-facility-indiana-2022-07-20/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=July 20, 2022 |title=SkyWater Plans to Build Advanced $1.8B Semiconductor Manufacturing Facility in Partnership with the State of Indiana and Purdue University |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20220720005657/en/SkyWater-Plans-to-Build-Advanced-1.8B-Semiconductor-Manufacturing-Facility-in-Partnership-with-the-State-of-Indiana-and-Purdue-University |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=www.businesswire.com |language=en |archive-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105162756/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20220720005657/en/SkyWater-Plans-to-Build-Advanced-1.8B-Semiconductor-Manufacturing-Facility-in-Partnership-with-the-State-of-Indiana-and-Purdue-University |url-status=live }}</ref>

After the act passed:

*In September 2022, [[Wolfspeed]] announced it will build the world's largest [[silicon carbide]] semiconductor plant in [[Chatham County, North Carolina]]. By 2030, the company expects to occupy more than one million square feet of manufacturing space across 445 acres, at a cost of $1.3 billion.  The first phase of development is supported by about $1 billion in incentives from state, county, and local governments, and the company intends to apply for CHIPS act money.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 9, 2022 |title=Wolfspeed Selects North Carolina for World's Largest Silicon Carbide Materials Facility |language=en-US |work=Wolfspeed press release |url=https://www.wolfspeed.com/company/news-events/news/wolfspeed-selects-north-carolina-for-worlds-largest-silicon-carbide-materials-facility/ |access-date=2023-04-17 |quote=In addition, the company hopes to apply for and obtain federal funding from the CHIPS and Science Act to accelerate the construction and build-out of the facility. |archive-date=April 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230417210901/https://www.wolfspeed.com/company/news-events/news/wolfspeed-selects-north-carolina-for-worlds-largest-silicon-carbide-materials-facility/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In October 2022, [[Micron Technology]] announced it will invest $20&nbsp;billion in a new chip factory in [[Clay, New York]], to take advantages of the subsidies in the Act and signaled it could expand its investments to $100&nbsp;billion over 20 years.{{ r | Politico 20220809 }}<ref name="WaPo_2022-10-04">{{Cite news |title=Chipmaker Micron to build $20 billion N.Y. factory amid semiconductor boom |language=en-US |newspaper=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2022/10/04/micron-chip-factory-new-york/ |access-date=2022-10-05 |issn=0190-8286 |quote=New York is giving Micron $5.5 billion in tax credits over the life of the project if the company meets certain employment targets. |archive-date=October 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221006002244/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2022/10/04/micron-chip-factory-new-york/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lohr |first=Steve |date=October 4, 2022 |title=Micron Pledges Up to $100 Billion for Semiconductor Factory in New York |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/04/technology/micron-chip-clay-syracuse.html |access-date=2022-10-06 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=October 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221006000024/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/04/technology/micron-chip-clay-syracuse.html |url-status=live }}</ref>  The state of New York granted the company $5.5&nbsp;billion in [[tax credits]] as an incentive to move there, if it meets employment promises.{{ r | WaPo_2022-10-04 }}
* In December 2022, TSMC announced the opening of the company's second chip plant in [[Arizona]], raising its investments in the state from $12&nbsp;billion to $40&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kinery |first=Emma |title=TSMC to up Arizona investment to $40 billion with second semiconductor chip plant |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/06/tsmc-to-up-arizona-investment-to-40-billion-with-second-semiconductor-chip-plant.html |access-date=2023-01-05 |website=CNBC |date=December 6, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=January 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230106112439/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/06/tsmc-to-up-arizona-investment-to-40-billion-with-second-semiconductor-chip-plant.html |url-status=live }}</ref> At that time, company officials said that construction costs in the U.S. were four to five times those in Taiwan (due to alleged higher costs of labor, red tape, and training) and that they were having difficulty finding qualified personnel (so some U.S. hires were sent for training in Taiwan for 12–18 months), so it will cost at least 50% more to make a TSMC chip in the United States than in Taiwan.<ref name="WSJ_2022-12-05">{{Cite news |last=Jie |first=Yang |date=2022-12-05 |title=TSMC's Arizona Chip Plant, Awaiting Biden Visit, Faces Birthing Pains – Taiwanese company cites high costs and shortage of skilled personnel as it pushes to open $12 billion factory next year |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tsmcs-arizona-chip-plant-awaiting-biden-visit-faces-birthing-pains-11670236129?mod=Searchresults_pos2&page=1 |quote=Mr. Biden has been pushing to bring more high-tech manufacturing to the U.S. In August, he signed a law that includes $52 billion in direct aid for building semiconductor plants, which lawmakers viewed as key to ensuring American technology leadership and securing supply chains. ... Mr. Chang said the cost of making chips in Arizona may be at least 50% higher than in Taiwan. |access-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230303023453/https://www.wsj.com/articles/tsmcs-arizona-chip-plant-awaiting-biden-visit-faces-birthing-pains-11670236129?mod=Searchresults_pos2&page=1 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Noah_SS">{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Noah |author-link=Noah Smith (writer) |date=2023-02-07 |title=The Build-Nothing Country – Stasis has become America's spoils system, and it can't go on. |url=https://noahpinion.substack.com/p/the-build-nothing-country?sd=pf |quote=TSMC, the Taiwanese company that recently agreed to build a big plant in Arizona, is running into major cost issues: |access-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230303023452/https://noahpinion.substack.com/p/the-build-nothing-country?sd=pf |url-status=live }}</ref> It was also reported that the project faced significant delays due to TSMC engaging in routine wage theft and not hiring unionized subcontractors to carry out pipe-fitting and other construction work properly, among other issues<ref name="Harris Jun222023"/> such as withholding necessary skills training;<ref name="Butler 2023">{{cite web | last=Butler | first=Aaron | title=My View: TSMC should not blame US workers for Phoenix construction delays | website=Phoenix Business Journal | date=July 26, 2023 | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2023/07/27/tsmc-worker-shortage-phoenix.html | access-date=April 27, 2024}}</ref> while in January 2024, TSMC said it had delayed the opening from 2026 to 2028 in order to evaluate the Biden administration's shifting approach to tax credits.<ref name="Toh 2024">{{cite web | last=Toh | first=Michelle | title=TSMC says its $40 billion chip project in Arizona faces a further delay | website=CNN | date=January 19, 2024 | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2024/01/19/tech/tsmc-taiwan-arizona-project-delay-intl-hnk/index.html | access-date=April 27, 2024}}</ref> In April 2024, multiple TSMC employees attested to the deep workplace cultural differences between Taiwanese and American engineers as a key factor in these delays.<ref name="Zhou 2024">{{cite web | last=Zhou | first=Viola | title=Inside TSMC's struggle to build a chip factory in the U.S. suburbs | website=Rest of World | date=April 23, 2024 | url=https://restofworld.org/2024/tsmc-arizona-expansion/ | access-date=April 27, 2024}}</ref> In March 2025, TSMC announced it would invest $100 billion more in the Arizona site, including more fabs and packaging facilities and a research center.<ref name="TSMC press release 2025-03-04">{{cite web |last=Huang|first=Wendell| title=TSMC Intends to Expand Its Investment in the United States to US$165 Billion to Power the Future of AI | website=Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company Limited | date=2025-03-04 | url=https://pr.tsmc.com/english/news/3210 | access-date=2025-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hupka |first1=Sasha |title=TSMC to speed up AZ expansion after record profits, soaring chip demand |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/money/business/tech/2025/07/17/taiwan-semiconductor-manufacturing-co-accelerating-arizona-production/85245780007/ |website=azcentral.com |publisher=Arizona Republic |access-date=30 July 2025}}</ref>
* In February 2023, [[Texas Instruments]] announced an $11 billion investment in a new 300-mm wafer fab in [[Lehi, Utah]].<ref name="Clarke 2023">{{Cite web |last=Clarke |first=Kaitlyn |date=February 15, 2023 |title=Texas Instruments To Build New Chip Factory in Lehi, Bringing Hundreds of Jobs to the State |url=https://business.utah.gov/tax-credits/texas-instruments-to-build-new-chip-factory-in-lehi-bringing-hundreds-of-jobs-to-the-state/ |access-date=March 9, 2023 |website=business.utah.gov |archive-date=March 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230309202429/https://business.utah.gov/tax-credits/texas-instruments-to-build-new-chip-factory-in-lehi-bringing-hundreds-of-jobs-to-the-state/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
